Issue Description:
Replacement for Issue ID 1258137 & Action ID 1311637




 Regulatory Requirement: 12 CFR 1005.11 Procedures for Resolving Errors
  (a) Definition of error
 (1) Types of transfers or inquiries covered. The term “error” means:
 (i) An unauthorized electronic fund transfer;
 (ii) An incorrect electronic fund transfer to or from the consumer's account;
 (iii) The omission of an electronic fund transfer from a periodic statement;
 (iv) A computational or bookkeeping error made by the financial institution relating to an electronic fund transfer;
 (v) The consumer's receipt of an incorrect amount of money from an electronic terminal;
 (vi) An electronic fund transfer not identified in accordance with § 1005.9 or § 1005.10(a); or
 (vii) The consumer's request for documentation required by § 1005.9 or § 1005.10(a) or for additional information or clarification concerning an electronic fund transfer, including a request the consumer makes to determine whether an error exists under paragraphs (a)(1)(i) through (vi) of this section.
 (2) Types of inquiries not covered. The term “error” does not include:
 (i) A routine inquiry about the consumer's account balance;
 (ii) A request for information for tax or other recordkeeping purposes; or
 (iii) A request for duplicate copies of documentation.


 Issue Description:
 The current Cash App Reg E dispute process flow does not encompass Cash Lending customer disputes of loan repayments (not the loan origination). The products in scope for this issue and relevant action plans are: Afterpay on Cash Card (APCAC), Retroactive Financing (Retro), and Borrow.

Our review noted that key activities to identify and understand obligations, assign responsibility, assess and monitor compliance as well as escalate, remediate and report instances of non-compliance have not been fully formalised, documented and implemented. Specifically:
 • Review of APT’s draft compliance register (the collections section specifically) at the time of fieldwork noted the following areas have not been documented:
 o Detailed description relevant regulatory obligations e.g. acts/standard;
 o How APT will comply with the respective obligations or a path to compliance, for example, existing or planned controls within APT and / or collections agencies to ensure compliance;
 o Responsible staff who is accountable of ensuring APT meets the specified regulatory obligations;
 o A summary of any legal interpretations (for example, servicing messages vs collections message and the appropriate timing of these). Whilst legal consultation has been sought in some parts, these are not documented and should be reviewed;
 o Assessment of compliance and identification of gaps including action plans to address these gaps.


 • There is currently no periodic scanning of regulatory changes in relation to collections activities across jurisdictions APT operates within. For example, in the US there are different collections guidelines and requirements by state.
 • There is no formalised program for on-going monitoring of compliance to legislative and / or regulatory requirements for collections management (i.e. risk based monitoring). Reliance is placed on the collections agencies to comply with local requirements and reporting of these are discussed at the monthly quality assurance meetings.
 • There is no requirement from APT for Debt Collection Agencies to maintain compliance registers, however, per management feedback, all agencies maintain a legislative obligation register (except for the UK) at the time of fieldwork. These compliance registers have not been assessed by APT for completeness and accuracy or to determine the appropriateness of the agency's control environment to meet these obligations. Management confirmed at this stage APT does not have the capability across regions to effectively assess the completeness of these registers.

A number of guideline documents have been created by the Product and Collections teams, which detail the steps to be performed for:
 • post communication strategy to customers by APT and collection agencies;
 • management of hardship;
 • unrecoverable debt write-off; and
 • on-going, monthly and quarterly quality assurance and performance measures over collection agencies.


 However, outside of the above guidelines there are no other formally documented policies or procedures governing the end to end collections management globally. Whilst collections processes have been established and operating for all regions, these processes have not been formally documented across all regions.

Our monthly global monitoring of customers completing identity verification checks before being permitted to complete an order using Afterpay identified;
 In Australia;
 1. On 17 December 2021, one new customer made a purchase over $1,000 however new customers are allocated a maximum $600 credit limit.
 2. Between, January 2021 and March 2022, 285 customers were permitted to make orders (predominantly Doordash) when they had failed to pass the AU digital/manual identification at registration/ onboarding with us (in accordance with Australian AML laws).

Requirement:
 20. Credit and financial institutions should consider the most effective way to monitor the ongoing adequacy and reliability of the remote customer onboarding solutions. They should consider one or more of, but not limited to, the following means:
 i. quality assurance testing;
 ii. automated critical alerts and notifications;
 iii. regular automated quality reports;
 iv. sample testing;
 v. manual reviews.


 Testing Results:
 The Compliance Quality Control framework does not include any references to the SIL Square EEA KYC Procedures. The Global QC Checklists form combines the United Kingdom and the European Union in the dropdown menus for business verification and customer due diligence but these only include procedures for the UK.
 Furthermore, GCMT reviewed a sample containing 20 quality control checks (period April 1, 2022 to Mar 31, 2023) and it was noted that no quality checks were performed for Ireland due to insufficient operations volume.

Per SFS BSA AML Policy (Board Approved 10-11-23), page 19, section 314(a) and 314(b) Information Sharing;
 Upon receipt of a 314(a) Request, the BSAO searches the Bank's records to determine whether it maintains or has maintained in the previous twelve months any Account for, or has engaged in any transaction with, each individual, entity, or organization named in the 314(a) Request. If a positive identification is made, FinCEN is notified of the match by the due date stated in the 314(a) Request. 


 In addition, Information Sharing Procedure - SFS, last updated 01/31/2023, page 4 states;
 For 314(a) screening of Savings customers, all the following data points must match to result in a potential match:
 Name;
 Alias (Individual)/DBA (Entity);
 Date of Birth (Individual); and
 Tax Identification Number


 Based on testing performed, 1 of 10 samples was not properly scanned by 314a savings screening logic. The logic failed to search bank records for the provided business tax identification number. The design of screening logic does not include filters for all tax identification number types included in FinCEN's request for information. 'TIN' number type is ignored.

Requirement: Regulation E — Electronic Fund Transfer Act 12 C.F.R § 1005.11 Procedures for resolving errors (c) Time limits and extent of investigation
 (1) Ten-day period. A financial institution shall investigate promptly and, except as otherwise provided in this paragraph (c),
 The institution shall determine whether an error occurred within 10 business days of receiving a notice of error; 
 The institution shall report the results to the consumer within three business days after completing its investigation; 
 The institution shall correct the error within one business day after determining that an error occurred.


 Finding Description: For 356 Reg E dispute cases tested for time limits, GCMT noted 3 cases (1%) failed to meet the regulatory required timeline. For cases processed in Toolbox, a denial decision should automatically be sent once the agent completed the workflow and pushed for notification. However, for the three exceptions identified, GCMT confirmed the agents properly followed the correct workflows and initiated the dispute denial in Toolbox but the system appeared to fail to deliver the notifications.

There do not appear to be sufficient controls in place to understand the full composition of customer relationships, linked accounts, and underlying products/use. Specifically, Cash App’s ability to link all accounts connected to a single user may be impaired because of limitations in the amount of information collected, particularly with unverified (Restricted) accounts, and this results in potential: 


 a) difficulties in detecting and monitoring instances where a customer’s aggregate account value exceeds predefined KYC thresholds, which could lead to instances where additional due diligence requirements go unfulfilled;
 b) uneven understanding of a single user’s risk across all of their accounts;
 c) challenges in performing basic screening;
 d) delays and inconsistencies in executing denylisting decisions; and incomplete understanding of the customer’s use of their accounts.
 e) incomplete understanding of the customer’s nature of business and/or intended use of a customer’s additional account(s) in instances where the account’s assessed risk may require


 [KYC] [High criticality #01] 


 [High criticality #01]

Regulation 19(1) of the MLR 17 requires firms to:


 -Establish and maintain policies, controls, and procedures to mitigate and manage effectively, the risk of money laundering and terrorist financing;
 -Regularly review and update policies, controls, and procedures;
 -Maintain a record in writing of:


 i. The policies, controls and proceduresestablished;
 ii. Any changes to those policies, controls and procedures made as a result of the review an update
 iii. The steps taken to communicate those policies, controls and procedures, or any change to them, within the relevant persons business BDO’s review found that SEL’s business model is almost wholly outsourced and relies heavily on Block and Group systems and controls to manage and monitor SEL’s financial crime risks, this includes drafting, updating, and implementing policies and procedures. Under the current process, the SEL MLRO has responsibility for reviewing and approving all policies and procedures prepared by the Global Policy & Governance team to ensure that they are aligned with UK requirements. All policies and procedures are reviewed on at least an annual basis and the Board is ultimately responsible for approving all policies and procedures and all relevant updates are notified to employees by email.


 SEL has a number of policies and procedures, which document the Firm’s financial crime systems and controls in place to monitor and manage its financial crime risk. Several documents were reviewed by the Skilled Person in order to assess the completeness of the policies and procedures, and whilst the review found that the ‘Square Anti- Money Laundering and Counter Terrorist Financing Program SquareUp Europe Limited’ provides an overview of the financial crime framework in place at SEL, including the relevant financial crime legislation and regulation applicable to SEL, it lacks the specificity in detailing the requirements of the UK legal and regulatory framework in respect of money laundering and financial crime. The lack of specificity leads to limited information as to how SEL are complying with the UK regulatory framework, for example, the ‘Program Document’ includes detail on PEPs, but does not specifically state EDD is required, and as part of the EDD process, SEL must obtain evidence of Source of Funds (’SoF’).

