Issue Description:
Enhanced Due Diligence 
 Regulation 33(1) requires firms to apply enhanced customer due diligence measures and enhanced ongoing monitoring in the following circumstances: 
 - any business relationship or transaction with a person established in a high-risk third country; 
 - if it is determined that a customer or potential customer is a PEP, or a family member or known close associate of a PEP; 
 - in any case where the relevant person discovers that a customer has provided false or stolen identification documentation or information and the relevant person proposes to continue to deal with that customer; 
 - in any case where: o a transaction is complex and unusually large, or there is an unusual pattern of transactions; and o the transaction or transactions have no apparent economic or legal purpose; and  in any other case which by its nature can present a higher risk of money laundering or terrorist financing. Regulation 33(4) states enhanced customer due diligence measures taken by a firm must include— a) as far as reasonably possible, examining the background and purpose of the transaction, and b) increasing the degree and nature of monitoring of the business relationship in which the transaction is made to determine whether that transaction or that relationship appear to be suspicious. Regulation 33(5) further states, that depending on the requirements of the case, the enhanced customer due diligence measures required under paragraph may also include: a) seeking additional independent, reliable sources to verify information provided or made available to the relevant person; b) taking additional measures to understand better the background, ownership and financial situation of the customer, and other parties to the transaction; c) taking further steps to be satisfied that the transaction is consistent with the purpose and intended nature of the business relationship; d) increasing the monitoring of the business relationship, including greater scrutiny of transactions. In line with SEL’s AML / CTF Program document, an EDD review will be triggered if an account meets one or more of the following factors: 
 - confirmed enforcement hits; and  confirmed PEP or RCA hit; EDD will be performed on the above accounts at the point of registration and checks include:  performing web searches on the Seller and its associated individuals, and email addresses and phone numbers provided;  confirming the MCC aligns with the expected activity of the Seller; 
 - performing additional negative news and/or criminal history searches. Where SEL is not comfortable the above checks have mitigated the increased risk, SEL will deactivate the Seller’s account and submit an RFI to understand the Seller’s activity further. Whilst SEL is performing some additional checks as part of its EDD process at the point of on-boarding, the Firm does not request evidence of Source of Wealth (’SoW’) for the business entity and its UBOs. Where SEL establishes a relationship with a PEP, as per Regulation 35(5)(b) it is a regulatory requirement to establish the SoW involved in the proposed business relationship. Further, Regulation 33(1) requires that where a business relationship or transaction is established with a high-risk third country, EDD is to be applied. Whilst it is unlikely SEL’s Sellers would have any connection with high-risk third countries, it is not impossible, and at present, SEL’s suite of policies and procedure do not reference the aforementioned requirements, therefore the Firm’s suite of Procedures should specifically outline the requirement to conduct EDD where said relationships or transactions are identified, or where this regulation is not applicable to SEL’s business model, this should be referenced within it ‘AML Program Document’. In addition to applying EDD in the circumstances outlined above, SEL’s AML / CTF Program document also notes that EDD will be applied:  if the account has a high-risk MCC; and  if the account is identified as high-risk as per the CRR. Despite the AML / CTF Program noting EDD is applied where a high-risk MCC is identified, this is contradictory to the CRR process as the MCC risk factor is not considered an override factor. Where an account is high-risk as per the factors above, the application of EDD is delayed until the Seller has a relationship age greater than 90 days and the Gross Payment Value (‘GPV’) has breached the average GPV for the MCC. In addition to the additional checks already noted as part of the EDD process, SEL will review the activity of the Seller ensuring:  prices are appropriate for the business type;  payment diversity levels are appropriate for the business;  any activity or patterns of activity are out of pattern for the business type;  there are no linked accounts or cards to the account; and  the business information (i.e., address, UBOs, and Directors) is accurate and up to date. Similar to the EDD process applied at the point of on-boarding, where any concerns are identified, SEL will deactivate the account and submit an RFI to Seller, including where appropriate, additional evidence on Source of Funds (’SoF’) and SoW. Although delaying the application of EDD as a result of high-risk classification of the CRR enables SEL to capture data on the Seller’s activity, and therefore, provides a greater understanding on the Sellers business activity, delaying the application of EDD until the relationship age is greater than 90 days, provides a significant period of time for an account to be used inappropriately, including the possibility of laundering funds or financing terrorism. In addition, where SEL also requires the GPV of a Seller to breach the average GPV for the MCC, this may further delay the application of EDD despite SEL’s own CRR model identifying the Seller as a risk. Further, incorporating the additional business activity questions recommended will enable SEL to understand the Seller’s business activity at the point of registration which will enable EDD checks to be completed either at the point of registration or at an age less than the current 90- day period. In respect of the new aCRR, as per SEL’s ‘UK Customer Risk Rating Rules’ created by the Firm on 14 November 2022, the new model will trigger an EDD review upon the following triggers occurring: 
 - at least 20 individual payments and at least one payment of each of the last 7 unique days; or 
 - £30,000 in lifetime GPV, regardless of the number of payments or unique days; and 
 - the aCRR score exceeds the threshold representing the 99th percentile. The model removes the need for a Seller to have established a relationship age greater than 90 days and therefore, the application of EDD checks may trigger at a sooner period of time. However, the model continues to require Seller’s to actively use SEL’s services before the application of EDD is applied. In addition, EDD will only be applied to those Seller’s whose aCRR score exceeds the threshold representing the 99th percentile, however, in-line with SEL’s testing results of the aCRR model, it identified that 50% of negatively actioned Seller’s had risk scores in the top 2%, therefore, the aCRR threshold of 99% is too high and would not capture all Seller’s that present a risk to SEL. As part of the control testing, BDO sampled 10 Sellers that had been categorised as high risk as per SEL’s CRR model. The following issues were identified:  for 9/10 high risk files reviewed, none had EDD checks conducted. For 3/10 Sellers, the relationship age was not greater than > 90 days and for the remaining 7 files, the GPV threshold had not been triggered. BDO note for 2/10 Sellers, no payments had been processed.

26.1 The Skilled Person’s review of SEL’s governance and oversight arrangements found that the Firm owns and maintains its own dedicated financial crime related policies and procedures. Our previous review noted that SEL’s that SEL’s business model was almost wholly outsourced and relied heavily on Block and Group systems and controls to manage and monitor SEL’s financial crime risks. This included drafting, updating, and implementing policies and procedures.


 As part of this review the Skilled Person noted that SEL has taken more ownership of its policies and procedures. The MLRO is responsible for reviewing and approving all policies and procedures, including any amendments made during the annual review process, and approval is also obtained by the SEL Board of Directors.


 While the Firm’s policies and procedures are aligned to Global policy standards, the Skilled Person found that SEL has more ownership and oversight to ensure that its suite of financial crime policies and procedures capture UK specific requirements. Our assessment identified that SEL has a number of policies and procedures, which document the Firm’s financial crime systems and controls in place to monitor and manage its financial crime risk. This includes primary documentation, such as the ‘Square Anti-Money Laundering and Counter Terrorist Financing Program SquareUp Europe Limited’. We observed that this document provides an overview of the financial crime framework in place at SEL and specifically references relevant financial crime legislation and regulation applicable to the Firm. For example, page four of this Policy references the UK's MLRs 2017 and the POCA 2002. Further, the Policy acknowledges that SEL is subject to the Electronic Money Regulations 2011 and the Payment Services Regulations 2017 as well as complying with the FCA's handbook. Finally, the Policy outlines that SEL’s financial crime framework is also informed by the US' OFAC sanctions regime as well as typologies from FATF and guidance from the JMLSG.


 Although improvements have been made to SEL’s financial crime framework whereby the design of its policies and procedures are more aligned to UK regulatory standards, the Skilled Person observed that further enhancements are required. As discussed throughout Workstream 3, there are elements within its AML framework which require greater specificity to ensure that its operational controls suitably adhere to UK regulatory standards. For example, BDO notes (within R38) that the design of the framework outlines that the Firm will capture and assess the nature and purpose of its merchants’ activity. However, our review of SEL’s automated merchant onboarding tool found that the information required to onboard merchants does not include:


 • description of the business (i.e., products and services sold);
 • average value of products and services; 
 • expected value of transaction (either weekly or monthly);
 • expected volume of transactions (either weekly or monthly); and
 • countries of operation (online point of sale only).


 Therefore, while the design of the financial crime policies and procedures more accurately reflect the MLR requirements, the design of the systems and controls used to onboard customers is limited as it does not clearly align to the Firm’s AML framework.

Regulatory Governance Committee
 The Skilled Person’s review of “SEL Compliance Update – Regulatory Governance Committee” reports identified that SEL has established a defined agenda for its Regulatory Governance Committees which ensures that financial crime related topics are a regulatory agenda item. BDO noted that the agenda includes:


 • Status of regulatory engagement/acquirers/banking partners;
 • Business Engagement & Projects Update;
 • Conduct & Consumer Protection Risk;
 • AML/CTF/FS Management Information;
 • Compliance Testing & Monitoring; and
 • Compliance Risk and Issue Log.


 Board Committee
 Our assessment of the Quarterly Board Compliance Committee Terms of Reference (“ToR”) noted that each Board Committee meeting must follow a defined template as documented within Appendix I ‘Template Agenda for Committee Meetings’ of the ToR. The standardised agenda includes the following items for discussion:


 • Administrative items;
 • Horizon scanning / policy updates;
 • Legal and regulatory updates;
 • Compliance and financial crime updates;
 • Finance update;
 • Enterprise risk update;
 • Privacy update;
 • Operational resilience update;
 • Outsourcing update;
 • Consumer protection / Customer success;
 • Business strategy updates;
 • Square loans;
 • Product proposals; and
 • Items for Board.


 Therefore, the Skilled Person’s review of SEL’s governance and oversight arrangements identified that progress has been made with ensuring a consistent approach to its RGC and Board Committee meetings is followed. Since our previous review, SEL has documented formalised agenda items for each committee and ensures that financial crime related matters are an ongoing point of discussion and permanent feature of its committee agendas.


 Committee Meeting Minutes Evidence


 Regulatory Governance Committee
 As part of our assessment of SEL’s Governance & Oversight arrangements the Skilled Person reviewed of the Regulatory Governance Committee meetings minutes for the periods September, October, and November 2023. The RGC minutes outline that the MLRO presents key financial crime information to the committee via regulatory and horizon scanning updates as well as presenting defined KRI and KPI data. The Skilled Person noted that SEL has adopted a consistent approach which enables clear and accessible tracking of trends through these periods. For example, the MI provided contains a four-period month-on-month comparison to aid the RGC with understanding the changes to its KRI and KPI data.


 Board Committee
 Similarly, the Skilled Person’s review of SEL’s Board meeting minutes identified that the Firm clearly presents financial crime related information to senior management. We noted that this includes discussions on each of the agenda points previously noted above. For example, The Skilled Person review of the Q1 Board MI Pack identified an unusual increase in customer name screening alerts generated for Q1 2023. We observed that the number of customer name screening alerts had increased by 21% from the previous quarter from 116,531 in Q4 2022 to 141,366 in Q1 2023. Comparatively, the increase of customer name screening alerts from Q3 2022 to Q4 2022 was 10.3%. A footnote within the MI Pack noted that the “increase of Cash Watchlist items QoQ is due to an increase in PEP alerts being created, as PEP cases below £800 are no longer being bulk closed”. Although the Skilled Person acknowledges that commentary was provided within the Board’s MI Pack to evidence the increase of customer name screening alerts, the corresponding Board Meeting Minutes do not evidence that this issue was either raised or discussed by attendees. Further, during the Q2 Board Committee, the Presenter outlined to the Board that the volume of customer name screening alerts had increased in Q2 which “was due to a rise in PEP alerts being generated as a result of comprehensive PEP screenings being conducted of the entire UK Cash App population in June”. Despite this, the Q2 Board Committee Meeting Minutes did not illustrate that committee members had questioned or challenged such issues. In addition, our review of the Board Committee minutes identified that SEL considered that it was on track to close the outstanding Skilled Person project actions by Q3, yet no discussion was observed regarding the overdue items. Therefore, despite the design improvements to the SEL’s Board MI packs, the effectiveness of how the MI is used in practice appears to show limitations from an action plan traceability perspective.


 Outsourcing Oversight Committee
 The Skilled Persons’s review of the OOC October meeting minutes identified evidence to demonstrate that committee members discussed and challenged risks associated with the KRI and KPI information presented. Section 3 of the OCC’s meeting minutes highlights that SLA’s were discussed. For example, when discussing ‘Cash CS Email SLAs’, the presenter noted that:  
 “the SLA was 34.5%, significantly lower than the 90% target. It was noted that investigations were underway to identify the cause of this shortfall. A committee member noted that the Regulatory Governance Committee may need to be informed of this issue”. 
 ’“ A committee member queried whether this should be escalated to the RGC, and a further committee member reiterated the importance of meeting these regulatory obligations and fixing issues when the data shows a failure to meet the relevant standards. ’ 
 However, while noting this area of good practice demonstrated by the Firm within its three committees which shows that discussions between attendees took place, the Skilled Person identified that the recorded minutes throughout the committee packs reviewed that while financial crime information was presented, there is no evidence to suggest that such information was discussed by any committee members across the OOC, RGC, or the Board committee meetings. 


 Through interviews held with the Executive Director and Head of Industry Relations, and the MLRO, the Skilled Person noted that Committee Packs for the OOC, RGC and Board meetings are provided to attendees in advance of the relevant committee so that all attendees have oversight of the discussion points and therefore have time to prepare specific questions during the meeting. The Skilled Person noted that, based on our review of the OOC, RGC and Board committee minutes, as well as our attendance of the January RGC committee, we observed examples where attendees raised points of discussion for the presenter, these topics did not relate to financial crime related matters. For example, during our attendance of the RGC committee, attendees raised questions regarding complaints SLAs. We noted that the reason for this is that there were particular risks identified within MI relating to this topic.


 During our interviews with both the Executive Director and Head of Industry Relations, and the MLRO, both interviewees highlighted the reason for a lack of discussion of financial crime related matters at the committee the Skilled Person attended was due to the MI which showed that the no risks had been identified. The Skilled Person acknowledges and agrees that the MI presented in each of the committee packs did not highlight any material risks or concerns. Nonetheless, while Compliance related topics were discussed, the Skilled Person found no evidence to suggest that financial crime related matters were discussed in any detail between committee attendees. This exposes SEL to the risk that its financial crime related discussions are limited to reactive assessments of risks which have already occurred, rather than proactively identifying areas of concern.

During our previous review, the Skilled Person identified limitations with SEL’s financial crime risk appetite statement (“RAS”). We also previously noted that while the Firm acknowledges it has no appetite for financial crime risk breaches or incidents that threaten the viability of SEL, there are no KRI’s or KPI’s considered as part of the RAS process. As a result, we found that it was not clear how SEL monitors and tracks adherence with its RAS on an ongoing basis.


 The Skilled Person’s current review of SEL’s financial crime RAS identified that the Firm has made enhancements to its approach to define its risk appetite. SEL records its appetite towards risk within its 'Risk Appetite Statement' which includes details towards a broad range of risks, such as risks relating to financial crime. This includes a definition of financial crime risk which it notes as:


 "The risk of breaching anti-money laundering legislation, or facilitating through customer / seller accounts, money laundering, terrorist financing or breaching financial sanctions...”.


 Further, the Firm states that "the Company has no appetite to be in a non-compliant position regarding its Financial Crime legal and regulatory obligations" and concludes that it has an overall "low" financial crime risk appetite.


 In addition, SEL describes the metrics which it has used to support its monitoring of its financial crime risks. This includes the specific risk metric, the capacity of metric (i.e., number of SARs per month), the risk tolerance, as well as risk appetite. Additionally, the Firm has defined the following terms as:
 • “Capacity” - the Company is operating beyond the maximum level of risk which the Company will tolerate. Breaching these triggers will require immediate escalation and corrective action where appropriate;
 • “Tolerance” - the Company is operating below the target operating range. At this point the Company will Closed an internal assessment of the risk indicator and the risk profile. The Company may choose to take corrective action based upon the outcome of the assessment; and
 • “Appetite” - the Company is operating at the target operating range as set by Senior Management / the Board. The Skilled Person noted that SEL has defined the following metrics and thresholds within its RAS:
 • % of SARs per transaction volumes (Capacity >6%), (Tolerance 4-6%), and (Appetite <4%);
 • Suspicious Activity Reporting Volumes (Capacity > 40 cases per month), (Tolerance 30-39 cases per month), and (Appetite <30 cases per month);
 • Enhanced due diligence - EDD to SAR rates (Capacity >35% of cases per month), (Tolerance 30%-35% of cases per month), and (Appetite <20% of cases per month);
 • Seller due diligence - high risk customer onboarding (Capacity >5% of onboardings per month), (Tolerance 3-4% of onboardings per month), and (Appetite <2% of onboardings per month);
 • PEP & Sanctions - Allowed open relationships (Capacity >0.1%), (Tolerance - N/A), and (Appetite <0.1%);
 • PEP & Sanctions - alerts to total transactions scanned (Capacity >1%), (Tolerance - N/A), and (Appetite 5%); and
 • % of customers onboarded versus offboarded (Capacity 20%), (Tolerance 15%), and (Appetite 5%). 


 While the Skilled Person noted areas of enhancements with SEL’s approach to assess and define its financial crime risk appetite, our review identified areas where further refinement is required. Our assessment of SEL’s financial crime RAS found limited evidence to suggest that it is aligned to the output of SEL’s BWRA. For example, we noted that the risk tolerances discussed in the RAS do not feature within its BWRA. Therefore, the lack of alignment between the BWRA and RAS limits SEL’s ability to identify whether the results of its BWRA suggests that the Firm is adhering to its financial crime RAS. Further, our review of the “PEP & Sanctions–Allowed open relationships” metric noted that SEL has a >0.1% capacity and >0.1% appetite towards PEP and sanctioned relationships. The Skilled Person found that the approach to conflate both its PEP and sanctioned customer tolerances could inappropriately suggests that it has a degree of risk acceptance to maintain relationships with sanctioned customers. 


 Additionally, our review identified that SEL’s risk metrics lack appropriate coverage to consider the effectiveness of its controls as they focus on whether the controls has led to a SAR being reported. The Skilled Person acknowledges that while this is an appropriate risk metric to understand how its controls impact the Firm’s SAR rates, additional risk metrics should be included to ensure adequate coverage of its risks and control performance. For example, the Skilled Person previously recommended that the following KRIs and KPIs which are yet to be included: 
 • % of clients onboarded in a week; 
 • % of screening alerts closed within 1 day; and
 • % of SARs investigated following an internal SAR within 10 days;
 • % of transaction monitoring alerts investigated within 30 days;
 • % of training assessments passed within three attempts;
 • % of high risk clients;
 • % of high-risk MCC’s;
 • % of Sellers with adverse media / enforcement alerts; and
 • % alerts triggered for ongoing monitoring review.


 In addition, as discussed in R32, our review of SEL's MI data presented to both the Board as well as to the RGC found that while broad KRI and KPI data points are captured, both sets of MI reports are not aligned to SEL's financial crime RAS.

The Skilled Person’s review of the Firm’s customer risk rating process noted that the process has been enhanced since the Stage 1report. In our previous report the CRR Model consisted of a single CRR tool while a new machine learning customer risk model called the Activation Customer Risk Rating (aCRR), was in the process of being fully integrated. As a result of this we have been unable to assess the new CRR model against the Skilled Person’s original recommendation.


 The current CRR Model operated by the Firm utilises two approaches, one at the point of onboarding a Merchant and one on an ongoing basis. The aCRR is conducted at onboarding and provides an assessment of the customer’s risk through assessing various variables to provide a day-to-day snapshot of the customer risk. The result of this assessment determines the level of scrutiny required through the customer journey. The initial risk rating takes in to consideration variables such as Merchant Code (“MCC”), product and service being sold, type of business and additional onboarding factors such as the screening results. These factors are then fed into a risk scoring between 0.0 and 1.0 where 0.0 indicated minimal risk and 1.0 indicated maximum risk.


 The Continuous Customer Risk Rating (“cCRR”) is a machine learning model which provides a continuous assessment of the customer risk rating, and the level of due diligence is determined by empirical customer risk, which is calculated using a variety of sources of information about the customer, as well as monitoring a customer against similar businesses operating in a similar geographic location.


 This information includes the factors included within the aCRR as well as ongoing monitoring factors such as transaction monitoring conducted on the business activity. The models set to determine the Empirical and Intrinsic Customer Risk are trained models using historical data within the Customer profile, which will then determine if Enhanced Due Diligence is required by the Compliance teams. The Skilled Person observed through the walkthrough that the average cCRR rating is taken over a 14-day period and therefore the cCRR is refreshed every 14 days.


 Similar to the aCRR, the cCRR also provides a risk rating score between 0.0 and 1.0, with 1.0 indicating maximum risk and 0.0 indicating minimal risk. The cCRR model leverages a wide range of information about the customer and their behaviour with the use of their transaction monitoring alerts that will feed into the risk scoring. However, the Skilled Person notes that both the policy documents for aCRR and cCRR do not clearly illustrate what variables are fed into the risk ratings. The Stage One review recommended that SEL enhances the CRR model to include additional variables such as the jurisdiction in which a seller operates in, the MCC risk rating, and the type of business ownership (e.g. sole proprietor, registered company, partnership). The Firm utilises over 500 input signals that feed into the cCRR, however it is unclear and not appropriately documented
 how these signals work and how exactly they inform the cCRR


 The Skilled Person also notes that both the aCRR and cCRR documents detail the process of implementing the technical aspect of conducting a customer risk assessment using the likes of empirical and intrinsic risk scoring, however there is a lack of detail around what specific information is considered that feeds into these risk scoring, such as:
 • Market in which the seller operates in;
 • Type of product/service being sold;
 • Jurisdiction in which the seller operates;
 • Jurisdiction in which a UBO resides in;
 • Estimated average transaction value;
 • Annual turnover;
 • How the seller receives payments; and
 • Age of business.


 The Skilled Person acknowledges that the Firm has in place a comprehensive set of alerts to monitor a Merchant and assesses its risk exposure accordingly, however this is not reflected in the Policy documents. The Skilled Person also notes that the Firm have in place intrinsic customer risk factors that are measured outside the empirical risk assessment that would influence the overall risk rating of the seller. Examples of this would include factors that SEL believes should be considered as high risk. A customer is considered to be intrinsically high risk if they display one or more intrinsic risk factors.

 Intrinsically high-risk customers are therefore subject to regular monitoring equal to or exceeding that of empirically high risk customers and therefore would be subject to Enhanced Due Diligence (“EDD”). Notwithstanding the above, the Skilled Person notes that SEL currently only considers PEP customers as an intrinsically high-risk factor that would override the overall risk rating and therefore do not consider other high risk factors such as SAR hit, adverse media or change in industry types to include higher risk industries or fraud related


 Finally, it was noted that one file was rated as Low-risk, however as per the SCA-438 log provided by SEL to the Skilled Person, a SAR Flag was stated as “True”. Due to the lack of reasoning and justification on file, there was no further explanation around both the SAR flag itself, or why the seller was still rated as low-risk. Where SEL has not captured appropriate information on file for specific customer risk, this raises questions around the appropriateness of the risk rating provided and the adequacy of the level of due diligence applied.

Since our previous review, the Skilled Person identified that Block, Inc. has performed a dedicated Transaction Monitoring Risk Assessment (“TMRA”) regarding the specific coverage of SEL’s TM controls. The TMRA considers 12 TM risk indicators and considers the appropriateness of its current controls in mitigating these risks. This includes considerations as to whether the coverage of SEL’s TM controls is sufficient. BDO noted that SEL's TMRA assesses the following 12 TM indicators:
 ● Transactions that are inconsistent with the business activities of the customer;
 ● The geographic destination or origin of a payment is considered to be high-risk;
 ● Transactions are abnormally large or occur more frequently for the customer or compared to other customers in their peer group;
 ● Transfers over a short period of time of low amounts that together represent a large sum of money;
 ● Transactions unexpectedly involving high-risk jurisdictions, sectors or individuals;
 ● The transaction being requested by the customer, or the size or pattern of transactions, is, without reasonable explanation, out of the ordinary range of services normally requested or is inconsistent with the experience of the firm in relation to the particular customer; ● Third parties making repayments on behalf of the customer, particularly when this is unexpected;
 ● Early repayment of loans or increased frequency/size of repayments;
 ● Payments being made from multiple bank accounts held by the customer;
 ● Debits being made shortly after credits of the same value are received;
 ● Accounts with low balances but a high volume of large debits and credits; and
 ● A customer who has entered into a business relationship with the firm uses the relationship for a single transaction or for only a very short period of time.
 Our review of the results of the SEL TMRA found that of the 12 risk indicators discussed within the TMRA, SEL’s current TM controls fully cover 2 indicators, partially cover a further 2 indicators, and did not cover the remaining 8 indicators. During an interview held with the MLRO, the interviewee opined that, despite not being responsible for performing the TMRA, they were comfortable that the risk indicators which were fully and partially covered by SEL’s TM controls were sufficient to meet the needs of the business.
 However, the Skilled Person noted several deficiencies with SEL’s TMRA. We observed that the design and performance of the TMRA process is owned by Block, Inc. While SEL supports with this control, it does not own the risks associated with performing this assessment. We also found no evidence of recorded commentaries within its TMRA to support how the assessments were performed. Further, we were unable to identify any evidence of either Block’s or SEL’s interpretation of the output of this assessment and to whether the results were aligned to its BWRA. For example, SEL recorded within its BWRA that its “Transaction Monitoring and Controls were evaluated to be adequate”. However, the TMRA suggests that the Firm’s TM controls are not adequate given that the current coverage of its TM controls is deficient as 10 of its risk indicators are not appropriately covered. Therefore, our review identified a lack of alignment between SEL’s BWRA and TMRA. Through discussions held with the MLRO, BDO were informed that the risk indicators considered within the TMRA are benchmarked against transactions associated with all of Block’s products. The MLRO opined that, as SEL does not offer all of the products associated with Block, several of the risk indicators within the TMRA are not applicable to the Firm. Therefore, SEL informed the Skilled Person that it is comfortable with some of the deficiencies highlighted within the TMRA do not present a material risk to the Firm. However, while BDO acknowledges this view, the Firm has not recorded this consideration within its TMRA or its financial crime framework.
 The Skilled Person acknowledges that SEL considers that part of the TMRA’s risk indicators are not relevant to its business. However, we noted that the absence of an action plan to clearly establish the process to possibly remediate any deficiencies identified by the TMRA with regard to the coverage of its TM rules and scenarios exposes the Firm to the risk that it is unable to effectively mitigate its TM coverage in a timely manner. Finally, despite being performed by Block, Inc., the Skilled Person was unable to clearly identify the specific owner of this assessment.

The Skilled Person’s review of SEL’s TM framework identified that the Firm has produced the ‘Square TM (UK) Guidance: Best Practices for Case Comments’ in order to provide analysts responsible for actioning TM alerts with further guidance as how to produce comments in line with SEL’s expectation for TM alert reviews. We observed that the TM Best Practice document provides guidance on the types of data points which analysts should consider within their investigations. For example, it provides the following guidance:
 • Commentary on the merchant’s line of business;
 • Commentary on the merchant’s processing activity;
 • Commentary on open-source information;
 • Additional considerations (i.e., ensuring alert created dates are referenced); and
 • Compliance monitoring box (i.e., references used for escalations, such as SAR escalations for Compliance review).


 The Skilled Person found that the TM Best Practice document provides adequate guidance to staff responsible for reviewing TM alerts in terms of signposting specific datapoints which should be considered as part of their reviews. Regarding the “Merchant Line of Business” commentary section, the Firm notes that staff should consider the merchant’s web presence, whether TM alert information aligns to the information received during onboarding, and considerations to high-risk industries or locations. While acknowledging the progress made by the Firm to provide guidance to staff regarding TM alert reviews, the Skilled Person noted that SEL’s TM Best Practice does not provide examples of good and bad practice of the types of commentary which the Firm deems as appropriate to resolve a TM alert.
 Operational Testing The Skilled Person’s review of SEL’s TM alerts found that the Firm has made some improvements with regard to the operational effectiveness of its TM controls. We noted that the rationales recorded by analysts broadly discuss the types of TM risks which were identified as well as their considerations as to whether the alerts represented a material risk to SEL. For example, the commentary recorded for a TM alert for Merchant MLGRT18K40X5V clearly recorded the analyst’s concerns and the steps taken to resolve the alert. SEL noted that “#Deactivate #High Risk #F150. Some Web presence, however, extremely unhealthy point of sale activity. Heavy declines, fraud chargebacks, round dollar transactions. Activity is too high to maintain. Escalated to SAR team. Account frozen and status changed to deactivated.”


 In addition, we found that in all cases that analysts would record whether the merchant’s transaction activity was in line with its business model. While we noted that this is an improvement from our Stage One review, the Skilled Person identified that analysts would not explain why the activity was consistent of a particular line of business. For example, commentary recorded within the TM alert disposition for Merchant REKGHYW2132VY found that the “account information and transaction activity is consistent with a legitimate business and no unusual activity was found.”


 In addition, the Skilled Person observed the following deficiencies with the operational effectiveness of SEL’s TM controls: • 8/20 of the TM alerts reviewed we found limitations with the quality of the narratives recorded by analysts which do not clearly illustrate the risks identified with the alert as well as the steps taken to reach their conclusions;
 • 2/20 TM alerts had inaccurate “MCC” codesassigned to the merchant profile;
 • 4/20 of TM alerts reviewed noted thatinconsistencies with the data held by SEL;
 • 1/20 of TM alerts reviewed, BDO noted that SEL’s30-day SLA was breached; and
 • 3/20 TM alerts reviewed by BDO; the alerts wereescalated to Compliance whereby each TM alertresolved.


 Therefore, the Skilled Person’s assessment of SEL’s TM framework identified that although the Firm has taken steps to enhance the design of its controls by providing detailed guidance documents for staff to improve the overall standard of alert dispositions, we found that this approach has yet to fully embed across SEL’s outsourced TM control function. As observed within our Stage One review, the Skilled Person noted that thematic inconsistencies remain across the TM samples tested.


 Further, this limitation is also compounded by the fact that SEL has provided no formal TM control related training to 1LoD staff. As noted in R52, SEL’s financial crime training is limited to general AML modules only. As a result of this, staff responsible for operating SEL’s TM controls have not received dedicated training relating to their role. The Skilled Person would expect that TM analysts are provided with specific TM systems and controls training which includes concepts, such as writing effective commentary to clearly outline the investigation which has taken place and how the analyst has arrived at their conclusions.

Result Background: 
 ECOA, UDAAP, and UDAP program pages 4 & 5, section 7 states the Bank performs the following activities for marketing materials;
 - Reviews all promotional materials, marketing scripts, and member agreements and disclosures to ensure that they fairly and adequately describe the terms. 
 - Clearly discloses all material limitations or conditions on the terms or availability of products or services;
 - Clearly informs Customers of contract provisions that permit a change in the terms and conditions of an agreement; 
 - Provides accompanying disclosures within the overall user experience that clearly disclose any limitations, conditions, or restrictions on the offer; and 
 - Tailors advertisements, promotional materials, disclosures, and scripts to take account of the sophistication and experience of the target audience. 


 Testing Result:
 The marketing collateral documentation uploaded into JIRA was missing disclosures. GCMT was unable to assess the email campaign marketing disclosures for compliance with Policy and Program requirements. A quality assurance review was not performed to detect the missing disclosures because the Jira ticket was not updated to "live" status.

Results Background:
 Servicemembers Civil Relief Act (SCRA) Program, page 6, Section C. Relief Request Tracker states Requests for Benefits and Protections can be made over the phone, email, or other written notice. The following information about all SCRA requests, regardless of outcome, are documented on a formal tracking log (“Relief Request Tracker”):
 1. Channel through which the SCRA request was made;
 2. Whether the request was verbal or written;
 3. Whether the request was denied or approved;
 4. Date relief was requested;
 5. Active Duty start and end date (if known);
 6. Date protections were provided or denied;
 7. Reason for denial of Benefits and Protections (where applicable);
 8. Date protections were removed.
 9. Customer ID Number
 Requests for Benefits and Protections are documented in the account notes and mirror the information logged on the tracker. Any notes cannot identify the Servicemember as a member of the National Guard of a Reserve component.


 Testing Result:
 4 of 4 samples tested were missing a Customer ID in the Relief Request Tracker, and the account notes in Regulator did not mirror the information logged on the tracker.

Closure Request Justification:
Product Compliance has satisfied all elements of the action plan tied to this issue. A summary of the work that been done is below:
 (1) The Cash App Lending Identity Theft Prevention/Red Flags Standard was reviewed and approved by CPC on Thursday, October 30, 2025;
 (2) The designated Block employee that will develop, administer and maintain oversight oversight of the identity theft program is the owner of the Standard (Business Product Compliance Lead, Lending & Credit);
 (3) Lending Employees received Red Flags Training as part of their most recent Consumer Protection Training; and 
 (4) Cash App exercises appropriate oversight of service provider arrangements given its on going relationships with its bank partners.

Issue Description:
The Lending Operations ECOA Procedure does not list all relevant credit decisions or actions taken that are currently in use by the business. Specially, the procedures do not account for Cash Lending Borrow and Retro products that are sent adverse action notices when applications are declined based on a variety of reasons, including; 
 Customer Identification Program declines, 
 failed velocity evaluations: and; 
 linked bank account activities.

Following scope discussions with Square Japan Compliance and APAC Privacy Counsel in August 2025, there is an acknowledgement that the current “Square Japan Personal Information Protection Management Policy” may not be appropriate within the current organizational structure.  


 This is based upon;
 Some formalized controls did not have processes put in place to complete these;  
 Ownership for controls has not been established or the incorrect ownership is assigned;
 Limited consideration given to the role played by functionalised roles within the Group; 


 This issue was identified as part of our scope discussions for GCMT's Q3 2025 review for Japan Online Factoring Association Program Implementation Review - Personal Information Protection Management Policy.
